Since it&#39;s not possible in java to have this kind of overloading, I found a solution which could resolve a similar problem, using Visitor pattern.

First let&#39;s say that the code below represent our domain object and we wont add any external dependency or implementation details to it (like mapping details) 

 

    // Domain Layer
     interface I {
        void accept(VisitorMapper visitorMapper);
      }

      static final class A implements I {
        @Override
        public void accept(VisitorMapper visitorMapper) {
          visitorMapper.visit(this);
        }
      }
      static final class B implements I {
        @Override
        public void accept(VisitorMapper visitorMapper) {
          visitorMapper.visit(this);
        }
      }

    interface VisitorMapper {
    
        void visit(A a);
    
        void visit(B b);
      }


As we can see in domain Layer there is no external dependency or implementation details of mapping logic.

In the code below we will represent the web layer, and we want to map our domain objects into Json representation and we print it to a PrintStream.

    // Web Layer 
      static class JsonVisitorMapper implements VisitorMapper {
    
        private final PrintStream out;
    
        JsonVisitorMapper(PrintStream out) {
          this.out = out;
        }
    
        @Override
        public void visit(A a) {
          out.println(&quot;&quot;&quot;
              {&quot;a&quot;: &quot;a&quot;}
              &quot;&quot;&quot;);
        }
    
        @Override
        public void visit(B b) {
          out.println(&quot;&quot;&quot;
              {&quot;b&quot;: &quot;b&quot;}
              &quot;&quot;&quot;);
        }
      }

And now let&#39;s wrap it up! 
Here is our main application :


    public static void main(String[] args) {
        VisitorMapper mapper = new JsonVisitorMapper(System.out);
        I a = new A();
        I b = new B();
        List&lt;I&gt; domainsObjects = List.of(a, b);
        domainsObjects.forEach(obj -&gt; obj.accept(mapper));
      }

And by this now we can map a list of different domain object to different representation in the same stream.

PS : 
PrintStream can be actually the `ResponseWriter` or a `List` or anything mutable.

In java, the &#39;identity&#39; of a method is __not just its name__. It&#39;s actually its name, _and_ the type it is in, _and_ the types of the parameter names (and  at the class file level, even the return type).

Thus, given `map(I i)` and `map(A a)`, those methods are _completely different_. It is __not possible__ to get dynamic dispatch going for the same reason it&#39;s not possible to make a call to `.foo(x)` somehow result in a call to `.bar(x)`.

Java does have dynamic dispatch, of course. There is a difference between overriding (which does dynamic dispatch) and overloading (which does not).

This is where java _does_ engage in dynamic dispatch:

```
class Parent {
  void foo() { System.out.println(&quot;Parent!&quot;); }
  void bar(Number n) { System.out.println(&quot;Parent!&quot;); }
}

class Child extends Parent {
  void foo() { System.out.println(&quot;Child!&quot;); }
  void bar(Integer n) { System.out.println(&quot;Child!&quot;); }
}

Parent p = new Child();
Number n = 5;
p.foo(); // prints &#39;Child!&#39;
p.bar(n); // prints &#39;Parent!&#39;
```

`foo()` in Child is an _override_. You can stick `@Override` on it and javac will compile it without complaint. (`@Override` doesn&#39;t make a method an override; it is merely compiler-checked documentation: javac refuses to compile a method with that annotation if it doesn&#39;t override anything. That&#39;s all it does. It&#39;s &#39;error or no-op&#39;).

`bar(Integer)`, however, is _not an override_ - if you stick that annotation on, it would cause a compilation error. Given that `bar(Integer)` is a completely different method, `p.bar(expr)` where `expr` is of type `Number` (even though that expression resolves to a reference to an object of type Integer, that is irrelevant, the compiler cannot know that, that&#39;s a runtime thing).

